  "final_answer": "Based on my investigation of Il Messaggero's coverage, the issue of July 26, 1943 is indeed absent from the archive. However, the July 27, 1943 edition provides extensive reporting on the dramatic events of July 25-26, the day after Mussolini's arrest.\n\nThe July 27 issue was dominated by news of the regime change. The front page announced \"La composizione del Governo Badoglio\" (The composition of the Badoglio Government), with the subtitle describing \"Un'altra giornata di entusiastiche dimostrazioni di popolo acclamante all'Italia, alle Forze Armate, al Re e al Maresciallo\" (Another day of enthusiastic demonstrations by the people acclaiming Italy, the Armed Forces, the King and the Marshal).\n\nThe newspaper reported that on the evening of July 25, at 11 PM, radio broadcasts announced that King Victor Emmanuel III had accepted Mussolini's resignation and appointed Marshal Pietro Badoglio as the new head of government. The paper published details of the Gran Consiglio meeting of July 24, which had voted on Dino Grandi's motion calling for the King to assume direct command of the armed forces—a vote that precipitated Mussolini's fall.\n\nIl Messaggero's coverage emphasized popular enthusiasm for the change. Article 1943-07-27_a066, \"Adunate non preordinate ed entusiasmo senza retorica\" (Unplanned gatherings and enthusiasm without rhetoric), described spontaneous crowds flooding Rome's streets on the night of July 25-26, shouting \"Viva l'Italia,\" \"Viva il Re,\" and \"Viva Badoglio.\" The article noted people singing Risorgimento hymns like the Inno di Mameli and the Canzone del Piave—nationalist songs that had been suppressed during the Fascist era.\n\nThe paper published Badoglio's appeal to Romans dated July 26 (article 1943-07-27_a048), calling for citizens to return to work and warning that demonstrations would not be tolerated. It also reported demonstrations throughout Italy on July 26, including in Milan, Florence, and Bologna (article 1943-07-27_a021).\n\nThe composition of Badoglio's military government was announced, with detailed biographies of ministers. Notably, the paper reported the appointment of Carmine Senise as Chief of Police—described as a restoration that \"suscita il plauso unanime\" (aroused unanimous applause).\n\nConspicuously absent was any mention of Mussolini's arrest or whereabouts—the newspaper simply reported his \"resignation\" and replacement, maintaining a careful official tone about this watershed moment in Italian history.",
